                    <h4 class="mt-3 h4">After University 2020</h4>
                    <p>
                        After University, I spend a lot of my time working in retail. I've learnt a lot of key skills in the
                        Jobs roles that I have had.
                        The main ones being
                    </p>
                    <h5 class="mt-3 h5">Time management</h5>
                    <p>
                        I've been able to develop my personal time management to a high standard. The steps I take to
                        manage my time are to first,
                        assess the task. Determine if it's a priority. I would usually have around 5 different tasks
                        during the day. Priority is how it affects the customer.
                        I then make either a mental or physical note of the task. Working on how long the task will take vs
                        how much time do I have?
                        For example, If I had to work 20 cages of produce, reduce items on RTC, help out on tills/self-service and dress the store. I would take the following approach
                        to calculate how long it will take to complete each task.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        work out how long I have to work each cage, discuss my plan with colleagues, learning
                        which tasks they were going to be doing. This was important because it allowed us to create a
                        support system for each other. So if I or another colleague completed a task early we were able
                        to help support each other.
                        work each cage within the time set I created for myself. start new tasks when they became the
                        priority.
                        The reductions had a set time they needed to be started and completed. So at 6 pm, they became
                        the priority. Whenever a colleague needed help serving customers that would always take top
                        priority.
                        Dressing the store would also be the final task of the day. Taking the least priority.
                        Taking this approach allows me to almost always meet my targets.
                    </p>

                    <h5 class="mt-3 h5">Communication</h5>
                    <p>
                        Working in retail has also allowed me to develop my communication skills, both with colleagues
                        and customers, I spoke in the previous paragraph about
                        how I was able to create good relationships with my colleagues and be someone who could be relied
                        upon within the team. Outside of work we still have good relationships.
                        I was also able to develop this skill with customers. I do this by being a friendly face and
                        trying to give them the support that they need.
                        I'm able to use my emotional intelligence to determine how the customer might be feeling. For
                        example, if they're frustrated I found that often the best approach is to be friendly and listen,
                        then help them. Sometimes this would involve showing them how something works such as a self-service machine. Or other times if they're in a rush fixing their issue quickly so that they can
                        go about their day.
                        Giving excellent customer service.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        A lot of this experience came from my time working in the COOP as part of a small team of about
                        20 people, however, there would normally be 4-5 people on a shift including management.
                        I've been able to use the skills learnt in this role in all my roles. Before I worked in the
                        COOP I received an employee of the month award for my customer service and hard work whilst I
                        worked front of house in Mcdonalds.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
